<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-755-399  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 755 399.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Dec 19 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Drivefone receives license to test PCN. (New York, Philadelphia,Boston) (personal computer network phones)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blankenhorn, Dana.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Drivefone Inc. (Licenses).andO;Ticker:    DFON.andO;Topic:     Cellular radioUnited States. Federal Communications CommissionMobile PhonesTestingGovernment Regulation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>DRIVEFONE RECEIVES LICENSE TO TEST PCN 12/19/90 PARAMUS, NEW JERSEY, U.S.A.,andO;1990 DEC 19 (NB) -- Drivefone, which wants to get into the manufacture ofpersonal communication network phones with a Korean partner, received FederalCommunications Commission approval to test the technology in New York,Philadelphia and Boston through July, 1992.andP;  The company expects initialconstruction and testing of its system during the second half of 1991.andM;Drivefone President Michael A. Pfeffer said that PCN will offer betterservice than today's cellular systems since cell sites and transmitters canbe located within a few hundred feet of one another, allowing for more callsto be transmitted in a given area.andP;  Also, PCN uses a higher, microwavefrequency for its calls than present cellular systems, which will also letmore people use the system without interference.andP;  Pfeiffer predicted chargesfor PCN calling will be half those of today's cellular systems, which usuallyaverage about 35 cents per minute, whether the cellular phone user is beingcalled or placing calls.andM;(Dana Blankenhorn/19901214/Press Contact: Drivefone, Lee Montellaro,201/843-6400 ext. 206)</TEXT></DOC>